title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Quaternions</html:dfn> is a generalization of the <fr:link
type="local"
href="complex-0001.xml"
addr="complex-0001"
title="Set of complex numbers">complex numbers</fr:link>, denoted as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {H}]]></fr:tex> (after William Hamilton) consisting of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[t+ix+jy+kz]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[t,x,y,z\in \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> are real numbers, where the imaginary "numbers" satisfy
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[i^{2}=j^{2}=k^{2}=ijk=-1.]]></fr:tex>
It's not hard to deduce that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[jk=-kj=i]]></fr:tex>
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[ki=-ik=j]]></fr:tex>
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[ij=-ji=k]]></fr:tex>
Addition is given by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(a+ib+jc+kd)+(t+ix+jy+kz)=(a+t)+i(b+x)+j(c+y)+k(d+z)]]></fr:tex>
and multiplication is given by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*} (a+ib+jc+kd)(t+ix+jy+kz) &=(at-bx-cy-dz)\\ &\quad +i(at+bx+cz-dy)\\ &\quad +j(ct-bz+cy+dx)\\ &\quad +k(az+by-cx+dt)\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>
This means the quaternions form a noncommutative ring.</fr:p>
 
   
